<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;var&gt;</code> element represents a variable in a mathematical expression or programming context. Vanilla Breeze styles it with italic text and an accent color (<code>var(--color-interactive)</code>) to visually distinguish variables from general italic text (<code>&lt;em&gt;</code>).</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Mathematical variables</strong> — <var>x</var>, <var>y</var>, <var>n</var> in equations</li>
      <li><strong>Programming variables</strong> — variable names referenced in prose</li>
      <li><strong>Placeholders</strong> — user-supplied values in instructions</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>When Not to Use</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Emphasis</strong> — use <code>&lt;em&gt;</code> instead</li>
      <li><strong>Code identifiers</strong> — use <code>&lt;code&gt;</code> for function names, classes, etc.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Examples</h2>

    <h3>Mathematical Variables</h3>
    <div class="example">
      <p>The area of a circle is <var>A</var> = <var>π</var><var>r</var><sup>2</sup>.</p>
      <p>Pythagorean theorem: <var>a</var><sup>2</sup> + <var>b</var><sup>2</sup> = <var>c</var><sup>2</sup></p>
    </div>

    <h3>Programming Variables</h3>
    <div class="example">
      <p>Set <var>maxRetries</var> to the desired number of attempts.</p>
      <p>The function returns <var>result</var> after processing all items.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Placeholder Values</h3>
    <div class="example">
      <p>Replace <var>your-api-key</var> with the key from your dashboard.</p>
      <p>Navigate to <code>https://example.com/users/<var>id</var></code></p>
    </div>

    <h3>var vs em vs code</h3>
    <p>Compare how each element renders:</p>
    <div class="example">
      <p><var>variable</var> — a variable (italic + accent color)</p>
      <p><em>emphasis</em> — stressed text (italic only)</p>
      <p><code>identifier</code> — code (monospace + background)</p>
    </div>
  </section>

